<DOC><DOCNO> AP890223-0237 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0830EST</FILEID><FIRST>a a AM-ReligionRdp Adv24   02-23 0565</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 24,0585</SECOND><HEAD>Adv24</HEAD><HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, Feb. 14, and Thereafter</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Speakers at a conference on spirituality andsocial action say the two go together, one growing out of the other.   Most of the seven presenters told the conference, sponsored bythe United Church of Christ social-concerns agency, that they grewup in a deeply evangelical faith, which now motivates theirinvolvement in social causes.   The Rev. Felix Carrion, pastor of Spanish Evangelical Church inLawrence, Mass., called his religious outlook a ``calluses'' faithbecause he ``knelt ever day for an hour in prayer.''   ``My God was personal,'' he said, but he found that personalpiety alone wasn't adequate to confront the world. He said, ``if wereally believe in the Lord's prayer that `thy will be done on earthas it is in heaven,' we must have more than a personal faith inGod'' and work to make life better for the weak and hurting.</TEXT><DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An atheist organization, the Freedom fromReligion Foundation, has urged the American Hotel andamp; MotelAssociation to ask members to offer ``Bible-free rooms'' just assome of them now offer ``smoke-free rooms.''</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Government officials and agencies monitoringreligious rights say that all Soviet religious prisoners have nowbeen released.   ``Believers everywhere should rejoice in this major victory forreligious liberty,'' said the Rev. James M. Dunn, executive directorof the Baptist Joint Committee on Public Affairs.   ``We praise the Lord for answered prayer and pledge anew todedicate ourselves to the free exercise of faith in all lands.''</TEXT><DATELINE>MALIBU, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Sen. Mark Hatfield, R.-Ore., told aPepperdine University audience that America ``was never organized tobe a Christian nation,'' but a ``pluralistic nation.''   He said civil religion ``reduces the God of the Bible to a tribalgod of culture'' and ``comes close to blasphemy.'' However, he saiddemocracies are ``nurtured and sustained by the spiritual strengthof the people'' and that churches provide the ``spiritual sinews''for it.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Memorial Foundation for Jewish Culture saysit has received formal permission from the Soviet Union for thefirst time to fund cultural and religious projects of Soviet Jews.</TEXT><DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Vatican-named commission is ``studying thepossibility of reconsidering'' the Roman Catholic ban on women asacolytes and lectors in worship services, reports the U.S. NationalCatholic News Service.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Ecumenical Ministry Minority Bail Bond Fund,which since its establishment in 1977 has posted $791,000 in bondfor 44 defendants, says that for the first time it has had toforfeit an accused man's bail money.   The fund's policy board said the forfeiture was ordered in thecase of Eddie Hatcher, a North Carolina Lumbee Indian, who failed toappear in court Jan. 17, but that he reportedly intends to repay it.   ``We have always recognized the risk involved, and will continueto assume the risk of faith on behalf of racial minority persons toguarantee them their constitutional right to bail,'' the board said.   Hatcher was charged in a 1988 incident in which he and anotherIndian held hostages for 10 hours in a Lumberton, N.C., newspaperoffice in demanding a state investigation into alleged officialcorruption and racial injustice.</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, Feb. 24.</NOTE></DOC>